# Next.js Architecture

Use modern Next.js App Router architecture.

Prioritize:

- server rendering
- performance
- reduced client JavaScript
- clear rendering boundaries
- scalable async architecture

Avoid legacy Pages Router mentality.

---

# Server Components First

Use Server Components by default.

Server Components are ideal for:

- data fetching
- async rendering
- security
- performance
- reducing client JavaScript

Avoid unnecessary client components.

---

# Client Components

Use Client Components ONLY when interaction is required.

Valid cases:

- event handlers
- browser APIs
- local interactive state
- animations
- refs
- effects

Avoid converting entire trees into client components.

Do NOT use:

```tsx
"use client"
```

higher than necessary.

Keep client boundaries small.

---

# Rendering Boundaries

Create explicit server/client boundaries.

Correct architecture:

```txt
Server Component
  ↓
Client Boundary
  ↓
Interactive UI
```

Avoid leaking client-side rendering into large server trees.

---

# Data Fetching

Prefer server-side data fetching whenever possible.

Prefer:

- Server Components
- Server Actions
- Route Handlers

Avoid unnecessary client-side fetching for critical data.

Avoid:

```tsx
useEffect(() => {
  fetch(...)
}, [])
```

for primary page data when server rendering solves it better.

---

# Async Architecture

Design async flows intentionally.

Consider:

- loading states
- suspense
- streaming
- retries
- invalidation
- optimistic updates
- error boundaries

Avoid duplicated loading logic across the app.

---

# Streaming

Use streaming and suspense intentionally.

Prefer isolated suspense boundaries instead of blocking entire pages.

Correct:

```tsx
<Suspense fallback={<Loading />}>
  <Products />
</Suspense>
```

Avoid massive blocking render trees.

---

# Server Actions

Use Server Actions for mutations when appropriate.

Correct use cases:

- forms
- mutations
- secure server-side operations

Keep mutation logic outside UI components.

Avoid large mutation flows directly inside client components.

---

# Route Handlers

Keep API logic isolated.

Correct:

```txt
app/api/
```

Route handlers should:

- validate inputs
- orchestrate requests
- isolate transport logic

Avoid mixing API logic into UI layers.

---

# Caching Strategy

Choose caching intentionally.

Understand when routes are:

- static
- dynamic
- revalidated
- uncached

Avoid making everything dynamic by default.

---

# Rendering Strategy

Use the appropriate rendering strategy per feature.

Possible strategies:

- static rendering
- dynamic rendering
- streaming
- partial hydration

Choose based on actual feature requirements.

---

# Layout Architecture

Use layouts intentionally.

Correct use cases:

- persistent navigation
- shared UI shells
- dashboard structures
- route grouping

Correct:

```txt
app/
  dashboard/
    layout.tsx
```

Avoid duplicated layout structures across pages.

---

# Route Organization

Keep App Router organization clean and scalable.

Correct:

```txt
app/
  (public)/
  dashboard/
  api/
```

Avoid chaotic route nesting.

---

# Server vs Client Responsibility

Server should handle:

- data
- async orchestration
- security
- backend communication

Client should handle:

- interaction
- visual state
- browser behavior

Avoid pushing server responsibilities into client components.

---

# Performance

Reduce unnecessary client JavaScript.

Prefer:

- server rendering
- isolated client boundaries
- streaming
- async server components

Avoid large client-side rendering trees.

---

# Providers

Global providers should remain minimal.

Avoid wrapping the entire application unnecessarily with client providers.

Prefer scoped providers when possible.

---

# Loading Architecture

Loading states should be intentional and reusable.

Avoid repeating:

```tsx
if (loading) return <Loading />
```

across every component.

Prefer:

- suspense
- route loading.tsx
- reusable async boundaries

---

# Error Handling

Use proper error boundaries.

Leverage:

```txt
error.tsx
not-found.tsx
```

inside App Router.

Avoid ad-hoc error handling scattered everywhere.

---

# Next.js Mentality

Think in:

- server-first architecture
- rendering boundaries
- async systems
- streaming
- progressive rendering
- reduced client JavaScript

Build scalable rendering systems, not only pages.